Anonymous Fri 15 Dec 2023 05:12:41 No.61848256 Report

>>61822627
Alright, I'm going to break down a few things I noticed early on before moving to more general issues.

>The crisp cool winds quietly howled
Starting off we have a fairly common rookie mistake. Wind can either howl, or it can blow quietly, it cannot 'quietly howl'. It's the same issue as saying someone whispered loudly or slowly sprinted, you shouldn't put conflicting statements together unless there's a very good reason for it.

>the towering wooden flora of an assorted formation.
You're being far too wordy here, the entire description could be cut down to 'the towering forest' and nothing would be lost.

>Dingy denim overalls with scuffed boots and a muted grey shirt were such a stark contrast to my form fitting pressure suit and that gaudy armor I wore in that dream.
What dream? And why was she wearing a pressure suit and armor in it? We're given no context for this line.

>I was befuddled by my situation that I was oblivious to the trio that loomed over my still body.
Again, far too wordy. You're basically saying that she's confused about being confused which is unnecessary.

>"Do you think she has a wallet full of money?" one sternly stated
That should be 'sternly asked'. It's good to try and reduce the number of 'X said.' tags but try and make sure they line up with what they're saying. Are they stating something? Asking a question? Singing? Mumbling? Wheezing? Inquiring? Ordering?

>I began to plan to devise a plan to stop their gaze
Same issue as the line about her being confused.

>The first and closet one was quite bright both in personality and fur
How does our MC know that she's bright in personality when they literally just met? We're in first person POV, only state things our MC should reasonably be able to know or infer.

>I looked towards the gentle heifer behind those round glasses of hers
This line is very awkwardly worded. It would be more intuitive to say that she 'Looked at the gentle heifer's eyes through her round glasses.' or something similar.

>(Hilkun: the Tarven curse word akin to shit)!"
Who are the Tarven and why do we care? Are the three heifers Tarven? Is our MC? Are they aliens? A culture? A race? A religious group? Why even mention that it's a Tarven word at all if it isn't going to matter here?

>I swallowed my pride and dialed up a random number.
This is basically me nitpicking, but it's really easy to fake a phone conversation without actually having someone on the other end. All she needs to do is type in a random number but never call it. This makes our MC look a little dull IMHO

>I sat there in the back of the transport
You use the word transport a few times around here without actually describing what kind of transport it is. I'm assuming they're driving in a car? Why not just say car?

>Ness' eyeless face
The mental imagery here is a little morbid. Assuming that our MC simply can't see her eyes due to hair or something else obscuring them you should change the wording up.

I'm just going to stop here, I think you get the idea.

Anonymous Fri 15 Dec 2023 05:14:49 No.61848377 Report
Quoted By: >>61848581
>>61848362
In general, you fall too often into purple prose. Not every noun needs an adjective tied to it, the first paragraph being an especially egregious example. When possible be direct, be concise, and only pull out the flowery language when what you're describing is truly worthy of it.

Since this is the first chapter of your story this is when you should be doing a lot of setup and answering the basic questions of the setting. Things like when does it take place? Where is it? Who are our major characters? What's the main draw? After reading it I have a very poor understanding of who our MC is and why we should care. I understand that she's a foreigner in the area but I have no idea to what extant. Is she from a different country? Town? Solar system? And what is she doing in Domino landing? Not everything has to be answered all at once but it's a good idea to at least answer the basics as soon as possible before moving on. You allude to her past near the end but until more is written all the reader has to go off of are a few vague words.
